# 3. Cross-Family Design Guidance

## 3.1 Build problem families, not one-off questions
A reusable assessment engine should treat each family as:
- a generator
- a solver
- a renderer
- a grader

## 3.2 Reuse one fact pattern across multiple families when possible
A mini-ledger can support:
- accounting-equation questions
- statement-completion questions
- full statement-construction questions
- subtotal questions

A merchandising timeline can support:
- payment amount questions
- income statement questions
- journal entry questions

This is one of the most important ways to expand the question bank without inventing disconnected data.

## 3.3 Separate business logic from UI
The accounting engine should know the answer before any interface is rendered. That makes it easier to:
- support multiple UI modes
- auto-grade consistently
- generate hints and worked solutions
- export to other platforms later

## 3.4 Favor partial-credit grading
Many problems in the PDF decompose naturally by:
- row
- field
- date block
- statement line

That should influence how generated problems are modeled.

## 3.5 Difficulty should be controlled by constraints, not just larger numbers
Better difficulty levers include:
- alternate recording methods
- seller vs buyer perspective
- contra accounts
- returns before discount calculation
- error-analysis scenarios that still balance vs do not balance
- statement placement requirements, not just arithmetic

---

# 4. Suggested Minimal Metadata per Generated Problem

Regardless of family, a generated problem should ideally carry:
- family name
- instructional objective
- stem text
- generated business facts
- correct answer in canonical form
- grading decomposition by subpart, row, or field
- difficulty tier
- feedback tags tied to common misconceptions

This is enough context for another project to build the React components without relying on this chat.

---

# 5. Closing Note

The BM Accounting PDF is best understood as a **blueprint for an algorithmic accounting assessment system**.

The key shift is:
- do not recreate the PDF as fixed screens
- recreate the underlying accounting families as generators and reusable interfaces

That is what makes an effectively infinite question bank possible.

